By differentiating $M(x,y) = 0$ with respect to x, we arrive at
$M_x + M_y \frac{dy}{dx} = 0$ and we identify

\begin{align*}
M_x &= 3x^2 y + 8xy^2\\
M_y &= x^3 + 8x^2y + 12y^2.\end{align*}

By computing

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}M_{xy} = M_{yx} = 3x^2 + 16xy\end{align*}

we see that it is exact and hence partial integration can be used to
solve it. Note that if

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}M_x = 3x^2 y + 8x y^2\end{align*}

then by integrating partially with respect to $x$, we have

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}M = x^3 y + 4x^2 y^2 + f(y)\end{align*}

for some function $f$ that does not depend on $x$. If we differentiate

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}M = x^3 y + 4x^2 y^2 + f(y)\end{align*}

with respect to $y$ keeping $x$ constant then

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}M_y = x^3 + 8x^2 y + f'(y) = x^3 + 8x^2 y + 12y^2\end{align*}

from our initial observations. We therefore find

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}f'(y) = 12y^2\end{align*}

so that $f(y) = 4y^3 + C$ for an arbitrary constant C.

Therefore,

\begin{align*}\displaystyle{}M(x,y) = x^3 y + 4x^2 y^2 + 4y^3 + C = 0\end{align*}

is the general solution to the ODE.
